  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime and drug trafficking\n- Initial focus was on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) - First major legislation requiring financial reporting\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US) - Made money laundering a federal crime\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established international standards\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act - Expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n3. International Development:\n- UN Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs (1988)\n- European Union Money Laundering Directives\n- Growing global cooperation on financial crime prevention\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- Comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency and digital currency regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- More sophisticated technological tracking methods\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with emerging financial technologies and global economic challenges.",
